title: For Sale:  1941 VKT Finnish Mosin Nagant
postcontent:
Hello!

I bought this thing back in the 1990's from a department store that happened to sell rifles. Think I shot one round through it since I purchased it. I refinished the stock, only "modification" to the rifle. The bolt/barrel/receiver all share the same serial number. 

Barrel markings are "VKT" with a "D" underneath, then serial #, then 1941. Making it a Finnish rifle. Two piece Finnish stock. Hex receiver.

Cons: Small bit of rust on the magazine exterior. Can see that in picture. Small bit of rust on forward sling swivel and trigger. Barrel bands are loose but looks like screws just need tightened. The extractor is broken/gone. I don't know why it broke, but it did the first time I used it. I had too many rifles at the time (as if there is such a thing) but having many, it was never a priority to fix. This is not some sort of collector rifle, if anyone even collects them lol. It's got scratches and discolored finish, plus the refinished wood, so it's a shooter IMO.

The barrel appears to be in good shape. 

I have lee reloading dies for this, and probably a few (~20) casings, perhaps some loaded rounds. All would go with.

postcontent:
10-30 ROUND
2-20 ROUND
1-10 ROUND

The next-generation PMAG 30 GEN M3 is a 30-round 5.56x45 NATO (.223 Remington) polymer magazine for AR15/M4 compatible weapons. Along with expanded feature set and compatibility, the GEN M3 incorporates new material technology and manufacturing processes for enhanced strength, durability, and reliability to exceed rigorous military performance specifications.

While the GEN M3 is optimized for Colt-spec AR15/M4 platforms, modified internal and external geometry also permits operation with a range of additional weapons such as the HK416/MR556A1/M27 IAR, British SA-80, FNSCAR MK 16/16S, and others.

Similar to the MOE PMAG, the GEN M3 features a long-life USGI-spec stainless steel spring, four-way anti-tilt follower and constant-curve internal geometry for reliable feeding, and simple tool-less disassembly to ease cleaning.

In addition, a redesigned bolt catch notch in the rear of the magazine provides increased bolt catch clearance, while an over-travel stop on the spine helps ensure the magazine will not over-insert on compatible weapons. Low profile ribs and new aggressive front and rear texture gives positive control of the GEN M3 in all environments, and a paint pen dot matrix has been added to the bottom panel of the body to allow easy marking by the end user for identification. The new, easy to disassemble flared floorplate aids extraction and handling of the magazine while providing improved drop protection, but is slightly slimmer than before for better compatibility with tight double and triple magazine pouches. An included pop-off Impact/Dust Cover can optionally be used to minimize debris intrusion and protect against potential damage to the top cartridge during storage and transit.

Features

Next-generation impact and crush resistant polymer construction
Modified dimensions allow for wider compatibility with non Colt-spec platforms
Constant-curve internal geometry for smooth feeding
Anti-tilt, self-lubricating follower for increased reliability
Long life USGI-spec stainless steel spring
Over-travel insertion stop on the spine
Ribbed gripping surface and new aggressive front and rear texture for positive magazine handling
Paint pen dot matrix panels on the bottom of the body to allow for identification marking
Flared floorplate aids magazine handling and disassembly yet is slim enough for use with many double and triple pouches
Pop-off Impact/Dust Cover to minimize debris intrusion and for ammunition protection in storage and transit
Made in U.S.A. Color: Black

title: For Sale:  Smith and Wesson, Model Number One, 2nd Issue Pocket revolver.
postcontent:
Smith and Wesson, Model Number One, 2nd Issue Pocket revolver. Serial# 24550
Features:
3 3/16 inch barrel.
7-shot 22. short cylinder.
 Tip-up barrel.
 Varnished rosewood grips.

Cylinder has nice markings with the correct 3 patents dated:
 Apr. 3, 1855, July, 5, 1859, and Dec. 18, 1860...All clear and legible. 
Top of the barrel reads; "SMITH & WESSON SPRINGFIELD. MASS." 
Serial number visible on bottom of butt of gun.

**The Model One was S&W's first successful revolver design and one of the world's very first cartridge revolvers.
It was also the world's first gun to be chambered in .22 rimfire.
However, .22 rimfire back in 1860 was not the potent stuff you can buy down at your local gun shop today, therefore, though it is in perfect firing condition, this firearm is not meant for firing anymore, best as a showpiece or an antique display.
There is expected wear due to time, but very little considering the age.
The rosewood grips are in great condition Action works nicely.
Tip-up barrel latch is still tight and locks up to the frame tightly.
A must have for collectors.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1922 d 'no mint mark' wheat penny
postcontent:
The 1922 "plain" or "no d" can be produced from four different die pairs. Die Pairs #1, #3 and #4 produce either 
a "weak D" or a "No D". Die Pair #2, which is the most desirable of the four die pairs, always produces a "No D". 

In 1922 only the Denver Mint was responsible for producing Lincoln Cents. Both Mints were busy producing 
millions of Silver Dollars. No nickels, dimes, quarters, or half dollars were produced in 1922. The creation of all 
four die pairs was the result of the Denver Mint running out of usable dies with thousands of cents needed to be 
struck to fill their quota. 

Die Pairs #1, #3 and #4 were the result of "mint grease", which is a combination of dirt, metal, and oil, filling the 
area of the mintmark. Mint grease would fill the mintmark gradually, resulting in different levels of "weakness". It 
is believed that the mint grease would fall out, then refill creating a cycle of normal D's, broken D's, weak D's, and 
no D's. When looking at circulated examples of 1922 D's, keep in mind that the mintmark could have simply be 
worn from use. Die Pairs #1, #3 and #4 have "weak reverses" because they were struck with worn reverse dies. 

Die Pair #2 is not believed to be the result of "mint grease". A pair of dies that were creating 1922 D's clashed 
together. The clash resulted in damage to both the obverse and reverse die. The reverse die was badly 
damaged, and replaced with a newer less worn die. The obverse die was reworked by a mint employee who 
erased all traces of the D mintmark while repairing and polishing the die. The result is a worn obverse die with no 
trace of a mintmark and a strong reverse die. 

All 1922 weak D or No D coins fall into one of 7 categories:
1. Die Pair #1 Weak D (Weak Reverse)
2. Die Pair #1 No D (Weak Reverse)
3. Die Pair #2 No D (Strong Reverse) also called 1922 Plain **************************
4. Die Pair #3 Weak D (Weak Reverse)
5. Die Pair #3 No D (Weak Reverse)
6. Die Pair #4 Weak D (Weak Reverse)
7. Die Pair #4 No D (Weak Reverse)

email or text is best, REDACTED, more pictures upon request

title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 21 Skeet 20 Gauge
postcontent:
I am the fourth owner of this 21. I found it here in Tucson in August of 2006. The previous owner was selling this 20 gauge Skeet model and an original Model 21 Skeet model in 410 bore, both of which were left to him by his father. The father bought both guns from the original owner here in Tucson on December 16th, 1976. The original owner had ordered both 21's through Mathews & Boucher in Rochester, New York on February 7th, 1952. The guns were built to his specifications and finally arrived at Mathews & Boucher where they transferred to the original owner on September 24th, 1952.

Once I took possession of the gun, I decided to send it to Connecticut Shotgun in New Britain, Connecticut to have the barrels and receiver reblued. There were a few spots of missing blue on the trigger plate, possibly from a few drops of blood, and some fine scratches on the barrels from what I assumed was from use in the field. The buttstock and forend wood were and still are just about perfect and needed no attention at all.

After about six weeks, Lou in the gun room at Connecticut Shotgun sent the gun back to me. His work on it was exceptional. It hasn't been fired since.

The length of the raised matted rib barrels is 28 inches. The left barrel is choked WS-2 and the right WS-1. The front sight is a Bradley red bead and the middle is the 94B Winchester white metal sight. The safety is non-automatic. The trigger is gold plated. The ejection is selective. Bore diameters by my CPS bore gauge are .616 for both barrels. The choke constriction on the left barrel measures just shy of .602 and the right comes in at .603 so in fact, the chokes run closer to modified. Quoting from Schwing's book on the 21 regarding chokes, it states on page 95 "Where constriction was slight, in the case of Winchester Skeet #1 and Winchester Skeet #2, choke diameter would vary with the bore."

The stock is the straight English style with the later Diamond pattern checkering on the slim beavertail forend. DAC is 1 5/8ths of an inch and DAH is 2 inches. LOP is 14 inches to the center of the checkered butt. The cast is neutral and the overall length is 44 and 5/8ths. It has "select nice wood" and a "medium comb - leaning to the thin side". Although the gold oval name plate is supposed to be engraved with the owner's initials according to the build sheet, there are no initials present. The oval is still slightly proud of the stock, so I think that he must have changed his mind about that. Weight is approximately 6 and 1/2 pounds. 

I'm not a dealer but I can go through a local dealer if needed at an additional cost to cover his transfer fee. The gun will be carefully packaged and shipped in a hard case. 

One like this doesn't come along often. I have been very careful to represent this desirable 21 as accurately as possible. As stated previously, this gun was reblued and serviced by Connecticut Shotgun and has not been fired since. It is in perfect working order if you choose to actually shoot it.
